This dream involved no substances, and is one of my weirdest to date. Last night I woke up in a starship where there was no euclidean geometry or gravity. Kind of like walking on a small planet with a lot of gravity, walking down a hall that took a 120 degree turn down gravity would simply shift. Sometimes walking you would fall down a hole and gravity would rotate 90 degrees. You get the idea. Space and time were not congruent. There were cameras everywhere, it was something of a surveillance state. It was some sort of higher educational facility, an intergalactic interdimensional consumerist surveillance state. I met a girl with green skin, short blueish black hair, freckles, and some kind of space soldier getup. She had a visor and some fins on her outfit and was not earthly at all, but quite humanoid, and quite attractive at that. She told me of the outside, the exit, and that unlike what we were taught we weren't floating through space, we were inside some giant living, breathing machine that was feeding off of us, watching our every move, learning about us. She told me there was an exit somewhere, and that she could help lead me towards it but only so far, and that once I went on that path I would be a criminal. I wanted to be free from that place so badly, from being watched, form being owned. I wanted to see the freedom, the nature, the world without being constantly plugged in and controlled. I wanted to live free. She taught me where to go, and I found myself in odd places I wasn't supposed to be. A blue man, analogous to her father but not biologically, was hell bent on killing me. I had to move quickly and avoid him. I would sometimes se his shadow followed by his grunting as he rounded the corner. He moved incredibly quickly, so there was no time to stop and look around, and I had to make sure not to circle back around because if I found myself in the same room twice he would be there and catch me.
After I got out of the living quarters, I was suddenly somewhere I had never seen before, unbelievably psychedelic and irregular. Strange, hexagonal hallways, moving, breathing, psychedelic and dmt-like, reds, greens, waves of energy moving up and down, colliding and changing color. There were pillars, columns, crystalline and symmetric, but constantly taking turns and bends and joining in with other areas. It was not very organic, but quite geometric. There was no organic irregularity even to the rigid areas, but there was no repetition either. It was like a psychedelic starship but constantly moving, breathing, and changing. I saw the shadow of the blue man many times as he got closer, and had to make sure not to make the same decision twice, even if the entrances to the different rooms were slightly different since the last time I had entered them. I had to keep a mental map of the area but it was nothing like usual as reality was so non-euclidean in nature. It was quite terrifying having someone constantly after you, ready to kill you at the slightest mistake. After I escaped that area, I was in some underground city, some large hub but also like a movie theater in its color pallete, just much less human. There were crossroads and people coming to and from entering different areas. I saw my best friend who I haven't communicated with in quite a long time. He spoke no words but simply pointed in the direction I needed to go. I also saw the girl on a cliff-like overhang on the wall, standing there, beckoning me to follow the same path he pointed to. Somehow I knew he was on the same path as he communicated to me without using any words or telepathy, I just knew what he meant, it was communication in the realm of pure meaning, not even in the realm of linguistic thought. I went through many different areas, some stages, there was a common theme of entertainment and products. It was like a giant intergallactic shopping mall.
The second crossroads was even more crowded, some kind of commercial hub with both humans, aliens, and non-material entities all moving around, darting around, buying, selling. Things went on like this for quite awhile, I believe there were 4 major areas I explored. The girl and my friend were there every time, but we each had to take different paths to reach the exit. The blue man had ceased watching me, but the cameras were everywhere, watching my every move. Someone, somewhere knew I was trying to escape. I finally made it and met up with my friend again, who pointed at an exit sign. There it was, freedom, but I also saw a room that intrigued me. It was a desert, a pink desert. There were all these other pocket dimensions lining the hall, left, right, up, down as the hall twisted in a spiral forward towards the exit. I simply had to see the desert. I entered the room. It was one room away from the exit, so I should be able to get back and dart out without someone seeing me enter the same room again. As I walked, things grew redder, my vision became less contrasted, blurrier, and all of a sudden my entire body felt pain. You aren't supposed to feel pain in a dream, but this was pain. I then woke up, but was so tired I fell back asleep, unable to move.
Targz 10-Mar-20 04:30 PM
This next part of the dream was the most intense but also the most realistic. In complete opposition to this psychedelic madness I was in before, I was now in a perfectly realistic world. I was driving with my dad in his car and we were moving out to a rural area. We were renting out a house temporarily while we searched for somewhere permanent to live, perhaps some place with some land to grow food or something. As we pulled into the driveway, I saw a girl exit the house next door with two younger sisters I had never seen. She immediately recognized me and I realized it was the girl I knew as a child 10 years ago that moved away one day once we started to get close. We had something quite pure as kids. I was 8 at the time (18 currently) that we met and we knew each other until I almost turned 10. Both our parents were teachers at the school so we always had somewhere to hang out after school. It was the first time I had ever felt something like that for someone, but it was something so pure, before sex or social circles were understood or part of the equation at all. It was some raw, unadultered feelings, not fuelled by any kind of lust or any social programming of how we were supposed to behave or anything, just some kind of mutual want to be close to that other person, to spend time with them, to share secrets, to be up next to them and hold them. It was my first experience with mutual attraction. Then one day out of nowhere her parents just moved her away and I never heard from her again. She had aged quite well, my brain doing a fantastic job at reconstructing some elements of her face from my vague, foggy memories yet taking some liberties with how she aged. I was invited to dinner with her family that night and so was my dad, and this is when things took an interesting turn.
Targz 10-Mar-20 04:37 PM
Everything about the experience felt so real, but I kept my mouth shut and ate food I normally wouldn't, I stayed quite instead of speaking my mind about what I believed in fear of looking like a radical nonconformist lunatic, and I sucked up, I wasn't true to myself or my beliefs I just wanted to reignite that raw feeling, without expectation or lust, just that feeling of being close to somebody, cared for, wanted. That raw feeling was twisted though, we slept together after that, the first dream of a sexual nature I've probably ever had, then we talked about what we wanted, a life together, and I lied through my teeth to be right for her. It wasn't all lies, but I bent my beliefs, I made exceptions to allow them to be compatible with that kind of lifestyle, for then, I was being offered happiness for the rest of my life, a simple life, a beautiful life, financial security, and a forever filling of that void inside of me granted I gave up my quest to save the world, to change the world, granted I gave up my beliefs, stopped being true to myself, and just became docile, agreeable. It was the ultimate forbidden fruit, an irresistable choice to give up my quest for making the world better for happiness for myself. When I agreed to spend my life like that after what felt like forever, so much anticipation and joy and belonging brewing, the prospect of a caring family and a loving girlfriend and a life free of worry or hardship, I made that final embrace and she vanished from my arms, and there I was lying in my bed, having betrayed myself, with nothing to show for it. The cameras did not lie. They saw my weakness, that greed, that compulsion for more. When I was so close to getting what I wanted, so close to enlightenment, I was offered a choice, and I chose wrong, and I lost everything. I woke up in a fog, lonely, sad, tired, blurry, having betrayed myself. That dream showed me how much I truly doubt myself, and how readily I gave up my journey for belonging.
This dream has been one of the most profound trip-like experiences I've had in recent time, and it was had without any substances at all. It brought up such a discourse inside of me, made me really question what I want, and in reality, while the drugs make it easy to embrace this ideology of mine, this mission, that loneliness, that desire to hold and be held, to love and be loved, was able to so easily make me betray myself. Who I truly thought I was wasn't me at all, I had thrown myself a curveball to hide my loneliness, under the guise taht I didn't want nor need that at all. I didn't heed the siren's song. I listened and I steered and I wrecked my ship. All of my spiritual progress set back significantly. When I was given that choice with nobody looking, without my rational self looking, my gut feeling was to go for it, and I lost it all. I am not in tune with myself like I thought I was. Closer than I was before perhaps, but that showed me how big of a discrepancy I had between my higher and lower mind, and how my substance use covered it up.
Targz 10-Mar-20 08:11 PM
What I realize now is that it was similar to other dreams I've had where I picked the enticing option thinking I'd get the benefits without any repercussions. My subconscious desires and wants misaligned with what my conscious knew was best for me and my mission and I was punished for it with that sense of doubt and confusion. Henceforth, now that I experienced punishment for going with my subconscious desire against what I believed was best, I'll be less likely to take that option.
Dreams are training simulators for the mind. Whether it be for simple motor programs or more advanced moral decisions.
